FUNDRAISING ALERT! 2021 PROM

#1: School has just begun and the Junior Class has been busy planning already for the 2021 prom set for May 1st. We have a great fundraising opportunity occurring now. Do you have gently used spirit wear that your kids have outgrown or from previous graduates? If so please consider donating them to our Prom Spirit Wear garage sale. Drop off sites include the RCC on top of the front desk, High school by the front office door, and Bankwest starting 9/8/2020. Further details regarding date, time, and location of the garage sale will be forthcoming.

#: A second opportunity to support Prom and to show your Rocket Spirit is to display the Rocket “R” on your driveway. Two different sizes are available, large at $45 and small at $30. Please contact Tracy Bremel at abilityandbeyond@cs.com to place your order.

*This is not an ISD 883 sponsored fundraiser.*

SMITH DEFENSIVE DRIVING TIPS.

Make the roads a safe place by employing the same methods we use with our drivers. The Smith System states that following these five rules can dramatically reduce the risk of major accidents on highways and roads. We will cover one tip daily this week.

1. Aim High
The first rule for this method is “Aim high in steering”. Staying alert of the dangers and traffic ahead not only avoids rear-end collisions, but it also alerts other drivers behind your vehicle to slow down. The driver should steer and focus their attention high, to view the road as whole and not just a few feet ahead.

Stop in today and APPLY.
Paid training. You are well prepared for all testing.
$800.00 sign on bonus. Paid at 3 and 6 months of driving.

Rockford Bus Service

Rockford MN 55373
763-477-6100

post_text:
Why do we stop at railroad crossings? The answer is probably obvious.

One day Mike was doing an RR stop. The warning lights were not flashing. Mike looked one way and looked the other. Much to his surprise, a train was moving and close. The crossing lights should have been on. The RR warning lights had failed.

RR crossings are a no passing zone, yet I get passed at one far too often. The passing vehicles are trusting that the warning lights are working and are driving into a blind and dangerous situation. Besides themselves, they are putting the entire bus at risk of GREAT harm. If caught, the driver can face a large fine upwards of $700.00. The possible charge may be a misdemeanor and include endangering others.

Please, slow down and look when crossing RR tracks. We are all worth it.

You can see the Roadie on bus 12.

APPLY TODAY
Paid training. You are well prepared for all testing.
$800.00 sign on bonus. Paid at 3 and 6 months of driving.

Stop in today.

Rockford Bus Service

Rockford MN 55373
763-477-6100

post_text:
Our very own Maddie Haas has participated (on her own!) in an incredible virtual choir organized by the choral composer Eric Whitacre. If you don’t know his name, he is a very famous musician in the choir world, and the person who first created a virtual choir about 10 years ago.

His sixth virtual choir is the one recently released, with over 17,000 singers from 129 countries, including Maddie! Her name is listed in the video at 5:48 in the bottom left of the screen. What a cool thing for her to do, and a beautiful song and sentiment! Enjoy some choral music in your day today! (Thank you Miriam Augsburger for sharing.)

https://www.youtube.com/watch?reload=9&v=InULYfJHKI0&feature=emb_logo

Monday, August 17, 8:00 am - 4:00 pm
Tuesday, August 18, 11:00 am - 7:00 pm
Wednesday, August 19, 8:00 am - 4:00 pm

Thank you!

post_text: IB FAQ: What are the three International Baccalaureate (IB) candidate programmes at RHS? We are a candidate school for the Middle Years Programme (MYP), Career-Related Programme (CP), and Diploma Programme (DP). When we become an IB World School, 9th and 10th graders will learn through MYP while our 11th and 12th graders will participate in the CP and DP. #IBMYP #IBCandidateSchool #Rockets883

post_text: Thank you to Mobile Hope for hosting Superintendent Dean and for gathering parents and students at the open house last week!
shared_text:
Mobile Hope
July 28 at 3:22 PM ·

We want to thank Rockford Area Schools ISD 883 and Superintendent Rhonda Dean for coming out to the Hope Center at Maple Hill Estates! She made an effort to discover the communities' ideas on what school might look like this fall and how distance learning can be improved for our students! Many students took time to meet and share great ideas and then parents had their own time with Ms. Dean to share their thoughts as well. You showed by coming out that this community is just as important as every other and that you value our input. We are glad to have Rockford serving Mobile Hope families!
text:
Thank you to Mobile Hope for hosting Superintendent Dean and for gathering parents and students at the open house last week!

Mobile Hope
July 28 at 3:22 PM ·

We want to thank Rockford Area Schools ISD 883 and Superintendent Rhonda Dean for coming out to the Hope Center at Maple Hill Estates! She made an effort to discover the communities' ideas on what school might look like this fall and how distance learning can be improved for our students! Many students took time to meet and share great ideas and then parents had their own time with Ms. Dean to share their thoughts as well. You showed by coming out that this community is just as important as every other and that you value our input. We are glad to have Rockford serving Mobile Hope families!

The School Board, administration and staff at Rockford Area Schools would like to give a HUGE thank you to the Rockford Area Schools community for their help and support for a fantastic graduation ceremony on May 30!

From organizing the senior parade to having mementos for each senior, this community gathered together to create a unique, memorable, drive-up graduation ceremony.

A special thank you to our community partners and the City of Rockford staff for their help in creating this one-of-a-kind graduation. We have heard from many parents who have expressed their gratitude for everything that was done for their senior this year.

Above all, thank you to the Rockford High School Class of 2020 for being THE class to be remembered in the history books! 💚🚀 #Rockets883

This year's John Philip Sousa Awards is Ellie Davis and this year's Louis Armstrong Award winner is Taylor Andres.

Congratulations to these two great students and to the entire senior class at Rockford! 👏🎶💚 #Rockets883

post_text:
The RHS music program had great success this year with all-state band and choir! Auditions for all-state took place in March. The audition process for all-state is made up of several parts with many hours of practice needed in order to complete.

The following students qualified as all-state alternates:
▪️Paige Henrich: Junior - Rockford band - Flute
▪️Steven Mutterer: Junior - Rockford band - Clarinet
▪️Madeline Haas: Junior - Rockford choir

In the event that someone else who made all-state cannot participate, one of the alternates may be notified.

Rockford had one student qualify for all-state:
▪️Amelie LaPlume: Sophomore - Rockford band - Bass Clarinet

Amelie is the younger sister to Armand LaPlume who was in all-state band 2 years ago (and also played bass clarinet).

The schedule for all-state this year is still a little uncertain. The current plan is for students to rehearse in February of 2021 and perform at Orchestra Hall in mid February.

Congratulations to our fine musicians!! 👏👏 #Rockets883

Exciting news from our #Rockets883 softball team! :D 🥎

Both seniors on the softball team (Madisyn R. and Amanda S.) earned the Academic All Star Award from the Minnesota Fastpitch Coaches Association for having a GPA at or above 3.75. 🌟

The team also earned the "Gold" Award for having a team GPA of 3.75 or higher: The Rockets team GPA was 3.90! :O

What an accomplishment! Way to go, Rockets!! 🚀💚

Another IB FAQ: What are the benefits of the Career-related Programme (CP)?

According to IB, CP students “develop personal qualities and professional skills, as well as intellectual habits required for lifelong learning.”

The CP core components include:
▪️Personal & Professional Skills
▪️Service Learning
▪️Language Development
▪️Reflective Project

#IBCandidateSchool #IBCP #Rockets883

Here’s another IB FAQ: How does a RHS student earn a full Diploma Programme degree?

Diploma Programme (DP) requirements include:
3 Standard Level + 3 Higher Level courses in their Junior and Senior years
Completion of DP core: Creativity, Activity & Service project, Extended Essay + Theory of Knowledge course

#IBCandidateSchool #IBDP #Rockets883

April 20-24 is Afterschool Professionals Week!

Galaxy Kids School-age Childcare team members are currently providing Emergency Childcare for essential workers in our community! We are so proud of our Galaxy Kids Team for engaging with our kids and community in such a positive manner, day in and day out, so our healthcare and other essential workers can focus on keeping our communities healthy and safe.

Thank you to the #Rockets883 Galaxy Kids Team for representing our district with PRIDE! 💚💚

Join us in thanking our Afterschool Professionals who make a positive impact on the lives of young people, during Afterschool Professionals Appreciation Week from April 20-24. Show us how you're celebrating by using the hashtag #HeartOfAfterschool.

#Rockets883 Fans:
Distance learning coupled with the uncertainty of what will happen beyond May 4, 2020, is not what any of us could have predicted, and it is certainly NOT how our Senior #Classof2020 expected to spend their last semester of high school.

On Thursday, April 9th our softball, baseball and turf stadium fields at Rockford High School will have their stadium lights turned on for 124 minutes beginning at 8:20 pm.

Why 124 minutes at 8:20 pm?
· Lights on for 124 minutes signifies the number of seniors at RHS.

· Lights on at 8:20 pm is equivalent to 20:20 in military time, again in honor of the Class of 2020.

#BeTheLightMN is a movement to give seniors hope for tomorrow and the future. Please consider joining us in this movement by turning on your porch/outside lights at 8:20 pm as well. We will get through this together - GO ROCKETS! 🚀

On Wednesday, March 25, 2020, Governor Walz issued an executive order that directs all Minnesotans to stay at home and limit movement out of their homes beyond essential needs effective Friday, March 27 at 11:59 p.m. to Friday, April 10. This two-week, stay-at-home order is to be followed by an additional three weeks of social distancing.

Based on the new order, distance learning has been extended through April 30, 2020. Governor Walz has indicated that at this time the intent is for school staff to return to work on Friday, May 1 and Monday, May 4 in order to prepare for students to return to school on Tuesday, May 5. The Governor stressed that this plan is subject for re-evaluation based on what happens with the evolving coronavirus situation.

Please visit our website for detailed information.

www.rockford.k12.mn.us

In today’s FAQ, we are answering: What are the three IB candidate programmes at RHS?

▪️The Middle Years Programme (MYP) provides a foundation for 9th and 10th graders.

▪️The Career-Related Programme (CP) helps prepare students for the workforce.

▪️The Diploma Programme (DP) provides students with a breadth and depth of knowledge they won’t find anywhere else.

#Rockets883 Community: Hennepin County Sheriff's Office is hosting a town hall at RHS TOMORROW (Wednesday) at 6pm.

The Hennepin County Sheriff’s Office and Sheriff David Hutchinson will host the first event in a planned quarterly town hall series in the RHS Auditorium. At each town hall event, the public is invited to hear Sheriff Hutchinson and a panel of experts speak on a public safety topic and answer questions from the audience.

#Rockets883 Fans: Your input is needed for our superintendent search process!

The Rockford Area Schools Board of Education has contracted with School Exec Connect, a superintendent search firm, to assist with the search to find the next superintendent. The Board is working the School Exec Connect consultants, Dr. Kenneth (Ken) Dragseth and Dr. David Clough to develop a hiring process.

We hope that you will give your input to assist in making the best selection possible through an opportunity to give confidential, written feedback to the consultants and complete the Survey Monkey form via our website, www.rockford.k12.mn.us. All replies will be kept confidential.

𝗣𝗹𝗲𝗮𝘀𝗲 𝘀𝘂𝗯𝗺𝗶𝘁 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗳𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗯𝗮𝗰𝗸 𝗯𝘆 𝗙𝗿𝗶𝗱𝗮𝘆, 𝗠𝗮𝗿𝗰𝗵 𝟲.

Using this information, the consultants will develop a profile of the desired skills and characteristics in the next superintendent. The Board plans to interview and offer a contract to a potential superintendent in April.

Thank you for your assistance! 🚀

On Tuesday, Dr. James Miller from Gustavus Adolphus College visited RHS to work with the Varsity Band and Concert Band.

Dr. Miller is currently on the faculty at Gustavus College as the Professor of the Gustavus Wind Orchestra and is known internationally as a director and clinician. Dr. Miller was able to offer feedback to the high school ensembles as they prepare for their winter concert on March 17th.

The Concert Band is also preparing for large group band contests on Wednesday, March 11th at Howard Lake High School.

Dr. Miller's visit was made possible by Rockford's Music Partners. 💚 #Rockets883

Seventh graders requested more outside time in Agri-Science this quarter. They didn't want to let the cold temps or snow stop them, so they are giving winter gardening a try! :O

Students built background knowledge of winter gardening, explored winter hardy seed options, and created their own "gardens" out of empty milk gallons, soil, and seeds.

After planting them in the snow, they will schedule time into their weeks to check progress and take observation notes. Agri-Science can also be a place for science experiments to happen! :D Stay tuned for updates on their garden!

#Rockets883

Rockford’s High School Jazz Band I performed on Saturday, Feb. 8 at the Bemidji State University Jazz Festival. Several jazz bands from Minnesota and Manitoba participated in this 2-day event.

Rockford performed, then worked with one of the guest clinicians for the hour-long time slot. Rockford’s clinician was nationally recognized music educator and bassist Tim Aucoin from Atlanta, Georgia. Tim Aucoin’s resume includes being recently recognized as the Atlanta Federation of Musicians Music Educator of the Year.

The jazz festival included an evening concert featuring the Bemidji State University’s top jazz band with guest soloists Tim Aucoin on bass and Kenni Holmen on saxophone.

#Rockets883

On Sunday, Feb. 2, two 8th grade Rockford students performed at Orchestra Hall in downtown Minneapolis as part of the Minnesota Youth Symphonies.

Elizabeth S. (flute) and Jane W. (oboe) are both members of the Philharmonic Orchestra conducted by James Bartsch. Minnesota Youth Symphonies is comprised of four major ensembles of students from throughout Minnesota who perform three times per season. Students audition and are placed into the appropriate ensemble for the season.

These two musicians are also members of the Rockford 8th grade band! Congratulations to our fine musicians on a wonderful performance! #Rockets883

post_text:
An important blue corduroy jacket was recently awarded to Rockford Middle FFA member, Cole Sundeen from the MN FFA Foundation. Cole is an eighth grade student who is part of the FFA leadership team at RMS-CES, participates in various CDEs including Milk Quality & Products along with Fish & Wildlife. In addition, Cole has played an integral part in growing the membership of the FFA program at the middle school level and tends to lead by example.

Cole was awarded his jacket through a program called “Blue Jackets Bright Futures” as support for his involvement in the FFA program. "A personalized FFA jacket provides recipients with a sense of pride while giving them ownership of their FFA experiences," said Lavyne Rada, Minnesota FFA Association Leadership Development Coordinator. “FFA plays an important role in developing agricultural and leadership skills in students while preparing them for their future careers.”

Congratulations, Cole! 👏 🚀 💚 #Rockets883

Seventh grade Agri-Science students worked on a few learning targets and standards this week:

1. Students began their Ag Literacy unit using 𝘈 𝘓𝘰𝘯𝘨 𝘞𝘢𝘭𝘬 𝘵𝘰 𝘞𝘢𝘵𝘦𝘳 (Linda Sue Park) with pre-reading stations and reading the first three chapters of the book.

2. Students prepped future lab materials by planting corn and soybeans under the grow lights.

3. Students worked on their Curiosity Projects that involve self-selected topics to research and then create a project to present next week during our gallery presentations.

Stay tuned to hear what they work on next! #Rockets883

REAMS Families: We're celebrating "Start With Hello" week next week! Students already understand the importance of kindness at REAMS. "Start With Hello" will take kindness to a new level and helps with inclusion for all students.

Here are our themed color days:
▪️Mon., 1/27 - Wear ❤️: Be the reason someone smiles today by greeting them with a friendly hello in French. Bonjour!

▪️Tues., 1/28 - Wear 💛: Be the reason someone feels happy today by including them in at recess and saying hello in Hmong. Nyob zoo

▪️Wed., 1/29 - Wear 🧡: Be the reason someone feels kindness today by making someone feel included in your classroom and saying hello in Korean. Ann-yeong

▪️Thurs., 1/30 - Wear 💙: Be the reason someone feels connected today by saying something kind to someone on the bus and saying hello in Finnish. Hyvaa pyvaa!

▪️Fri., 1/31 - Wear 💚: Be the reason someone feels joyful today by sitting with someone new at lunch. Say hello to someone in Spanish by saying Hola!

#StartWithHello #KindnessWins #Rockets883

Rockford School Board Member Jessica Johnson was recently recognized with a Director’s Award by the Minnesota School Board Association (MSBA).

The Director’s Award is awarded to MSBA members who have attained 100 or more points of attendance at their training programs within the past four years of their term. She joins 32 other Minnesota school board members with this accomplishment.

Johnson was honored during a recognition luncheon held during the annual MSBA Leadership Conference. She has been a member of the Rockford School Board since 2017.

Thank you for your service to our district! #Rockets883

The room was quiet, the tension was mounting, not even a buzz of the bee was heard... Rockford’s annual District Spelling Bee was in progress! 🐝

Twenty-five 5th-8th grade students displayed their spelling abilities in the district-level spelldown today. In the 18th round, after 9 rounds going head to head with 5th grader Alyssa G., 7th grader Lizzie K. reigned our RMS Spelling Bee champion!

Her winning word was “successor.” Congratulations, Lizzie!

Lizzzie will go on to represent Rockford Area Schools at the Regional Spelling Bee on February 5th in Sartell, MN.

Congratulations to all of Rockford’s qualifying Spelling Bee participants! :D 💚

#Rockets883: The next Music Partners meeting is Monday, January 13 at 7:00pm in the high school choir room.

What is Music Partners?
Music Partners is a non-profit organization under the umbrella of Rocket Boosters with the mission of supporting music K-12 at Rockford Schools. Over the years, Music Partners has raised thousands of dollars to support various projects, guest conductors and clinicians, and most importantly, our students at Rockford.

Music Partners is always looking for more help! Music Partners meets once a month to organize fundraising projects and go through requests by the music staff. The commitment is small and the reward to our school is huge!!

Consider stopping by at the next meeting! Thanks for your continued support of music at Rockford! 🎷🎺

#Rockets883 families: Did you know that several of our teachers are piloting an online resource called Mobymax that can help our students learn and practice math, reading, social studies, and science concepts??

Over the winter break, students can use MobyMax to help them stay sharp. MobyMax works best when used for 15-45 min. during the course of a day. MobyMax will provide mini lessons and then quiz the students on the topic.

Logins:
▪️Grades K-2: Selected classes may login using links from teacher website or handouts.
▪️Grades 3-4: http://MobyMax.com/MN1980
▪️Grades 5-8: http://MobyMax.com/MN1982

Note: For grades 3-8, students log in to MobyMax using the same username and password they use to log on to the Chromebooks and Google Classroom.

This week RMS-CES turned into a Civil War archaeological excavation site for our 7th graders! Budding archaeologists unearthed authentic artifacts, over 160 years old, from the Civil War era. They used their keen inference skills to determine what the relics were and what they could have been used for.

Our archaeologists really dug this project! :D

#CleverPun #Rockets883 #HandsOnLearning

post_text:
Four of Rockford’s 8th grade students were selected to participate in this year’s Central MN Band Director’s Association Honor Band. The band is comprised of nominated students throughout central Minnesota. The festival takes place on Saturday, January 11th at Elk River High School.

The four students are (left to right):
▪️Sarah B. on baritone
▪️Elise D. on trumpet
▪️Auryn R. on flute
▪️Chase E. on tuba

The band program also has 5 students that just completed the audition process for the MN Directors Association All-State Band for grades 6-8. This band is a highly competitive ensemble made up of the best musicians in the state. Chase E., who performed in this ensemble last year, once again tried out. Other students that completed the audition process include Robbie F. on trombone, Auryn R. on flute, Elise D. on trumpet, and Haedyn B. on alto saxophone.

Congratulations and good luck to our fine musicians!!

#Rockets883

These agriscience students put their engineering skills to work! Students used the engineering design process to created paper bridges of different styles, like with this “High Bridge Challenge.” For this challenge, students collaborated with team members to design the strongest bridge using strategies discussed in class.

Special thanks to Wright County Extension 4H specialist, Kelly Strei, for introducing our sixth graders to this project! #Rockets883

'Tis the season for holiday music!! 🎶

Last weekend, members of the RHS band performed at the Rockford Public Library TWO days in a row! Were you lucky enough to catch a performance??

▪️Friday's performance was at the "Ferdig Friday" event when band students perform at the library the first Friday of each month during the school year. Students performing on Friday included: Laney (flute), Cortney (clarinet), Taylor (saxophone), Elliot (bass), Kate (flute), and Claire (bass clarinet).

▪️On Saturday, the band program joined the Rockford Chamber Choir at the library. Students performing included (pictured from left to right): Libby (trombone), Gigi (trumpet), Claire (trumpet), Chris (tenor saxophone), Sydney (flute), Ben (baritone), and Sean (trombone). Ellie and Jessica (flute) also performed.

#Rockets883

Our mailbox was full today as our students' Sport in Society Advocacy letters were sent out!

Students sent letters advocating for change to MSHSL, NCAA, NBA, MLB, NFL, Major League Soccer (MLS), @NASCAR, and more! Some of the topics they addressed included sportsmanship concerns, visibility of women's sports on television, and drug use in athletes.

Our students researched their topics and wrote wonderful letters. We hope they receive letters back! #Rockets883

Our fourth grade Rockets participated in the “Kindness Retreat” put on by Youth Frontiers recently. Their main goals and objectives for the students were to be kind, participate and have fun. The students worked with leaders from Youth Frontiers and several Rockford Middle School WEB (Where Everybody Belongs) students who were their group leaders.

It was a record-setting year for the kindness retreat: Six sets of fourth/eighth grade siblings, five Sawyers and one set of fourth grade twins! :D

It was a day of high energy, deep thinking and looking for ways to work together to treat everyone they encounter in a positive, kind manner. What an amazing experience for our fourth grade students and teachers! #Rockets883
